{{palaeo-stub}}

'''David George Haskell''' is a British-born [[United States|American]] biologist, author, and professor of biology at [[Sewanee: The University of the South]], in [[Sewanee, Tennessee]]. In addition to scientific papers, he has written essays, poems, op-eds,<ref>{{cite web|last=Haskell|first=David George|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/30/opinion/natures-case-for-same-sex-marriage.html|title=Nature's Case for Same-Sex Marriage|work=The New York Times|date=March 29, 2013}}</ref> and the book ''[[The Forest Unseen]]'' ([[Viking Press]], [[Penguin Random House]] 2012) and ''The Songs of Trees'' ([[Viking Press]], [[Penguin Random House]] 2017).
''[[The Forest Unseen]]'' was winner of the 2013 [[National Academies Communication Award]] for Best Book,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www8.nationalacademies.org/onpinews/newsitem.aspx?RecordID=09052013A|title=Academies Announce 2013 Communication Award Winners|publisher=The National Academies of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine |date=September 5, 2013}}</ref> finalist for the [[2013 Pulitzer Prize]] in General Nonfiction,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pulitzer.org/citation/2013-General-Nonfiction|title=2013 Pulitzer Prizes|publisher=The Pulitzer Prizes|accessdate=December 5, 2016}}</ref> runner-up for the 2013 [[PEN/E. O. Wilson Literary Science Writing Award]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pen.org/literature/2013-pene-o-wilson-literary-science-writing-award|title=2013 PEN/E. O. Wilson Literary Science Writing Award |publisher=PEN America|accessdate=December 5, 2016}}</ref> winner of the 2012 [[National Outdoor Book Award]] for Natural History Literature, and the 2013 Reed Environmental Writing Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southernenvironment.org/projects/reed-environmental-writing-award|title=Reed Environmental Writing Award |publisher=Southern Environmental Law Center|accessdate=December 5, 2016}}</ref> ''The Forest Unseen'' has been translated into ten languages and was winner of the 2016 Dapeng Nature Book Award in China.
Haskell's second book, ''The Songs of Trees'', was published in April 2017 by Viking. It won the 2018 [[John Burroughs Medal]] for Distinguished Natural History Writing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.johnburroughsassociation.org/component/zoo/item/david-haskell-wins-2018-burroughs-medal|title=DAVID HASKELL WINS 2018 BURROUGHS MEDAL |publisher=John Burroughs Association|accessdate=March 12, 2018}}</ref> [[Public Radio International]]'s [[Science Friday]] named ''The Songs of Trees'' of the Best Science Books of 2017,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sciencefriday.com/segments/the-best-science-books-of-2017/|title=The Best Science Books Of 2017|publisher=Science Friday, PRI|accessdate=March 12, 2018}}</ref> [[Maria Popova]] included the book in [[Brain Pickings]] Favorite Science Books of 2017,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brainpickings.org/2017/12/13/best-science-books-2017/|title=7 Favorite Science Books of 2017|publisher=Brain Pickings|accessdate=March 12, 2018}}</ref> and [[Forbes.com]] named the book one of 10 Best Environment, Climate Science and Conservation Books of 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/grrlscientist/2018/01/26/the-10-best-environment-climate-science-and-conservation-books-of-2017/|title=The 10 Best Environment, Climate Science and Conservation Books of 2017|publisher=forbes.com|accessdate=March 12, 2018}}</ref>
Haskell received his B.A. in zoology from the [[University of Oxford]] and his Ph.D. in evolutionary biology from [[Cornell University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://biology.sewanee.edu/facstaff/haskell|title=Academics • Biology • Faculty & Staff: David George Haskell |publisher=The University of the South|accessdate=December 5, 2016}}</ref> In 2009 he was named the [[Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching|Carnegie]]-[[Council for Advancement and Support of Education|CASE]] Professor of the Year in Tennessee.<ref>{{cite news|title=David Haskell named Tennessee’s top professor |url=http://news-archive.sewanee.edu/people/2009/11/18/david-haskell-named-tennessees-top-professor|work=Sewanee Today |publisher=Sewanee: The University of the South|date=November 18, 2009}}</ref> He was awarded a [[Guggenheim Fellowship]] by the [[John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=David Haskell|url=http://www.gf.org/fellows/all-fellows/david-haskell/|publisher=John Simon Guggenheim Foundation|accessdate=December 5, 2016}}</ref>
