'''IGR J17329-2731'''<ref name=bozzo/> as described by [[European Space Agency]] [[Observational astronomy|astronomers]] is a single faint [[Transient astronomical event|transient]] [[Astronomical radio source|X-ray source]] ([[The Astronomer's Telegram|ATel]] #10644) observed with [[Neil Gehrels Swift Observatory#X-ray Telescope (XRT)|Swift/XRT]] on 16 August 2017 from 2:26 to 2:45 [[UTC]] with an effective exposure of time of 1 [[Kilosecond|ks]]. It was detected within the positional uncertainty provided by [[INTEGRAL]] IBIS imagery.<ref name=iau/> It was described as the [[Cosmogony|birth]] of a [[Symbiotic binary|symbiotic]] [[X-ray binary]],<ref name=bozzo/> a "first" in the lifecycle of an [[interacting binary star]], or a zombie [[neutron star]] brought back to life by its neighboring [[red giant]]. When first described in 2017, it was seen as an [[X-ray]] flare "[[outer space|from an unknown]] [[Radio wave|source]]" in the direction from the [[Galactic Center|galactic (Milky Way) center]].<ref name=zombie/>

