e (Norway) – Another extreme weather event named by Norwegian Meteorological Institute as Kyrre affected north (Nordland and Troms) Norway on 13–14 March with extreme precipitation and wind. Up to 90&nbsp;mm fell in 24 hours, flooding, landslides and closing roads in Nordland and Troms.<ref name="Toppe" /> * Carl (DMI) Ev (FUB) – 14–15 March. An intense low pressure brought high winds which damaged buildings and forestry in southern Norway on 14 March, with [[Hordaland]] recording the strongest winds in 20 years.<ref name="Toppe" /> though the low didn't reach hurricane strength in Denmark.<ref>{{cite news|title=Stormen Carl er blæst videre efter et kort visit|url=http://politiken.dk/indland/vejret/ECE2235897/stormen-carl-er-blaest-videre-efter-et-kort-visit/|accessdate=7 April 2014|newspaper=Politiken|date=15 March 2014|language=Danish}}</ref> Investigated by Perils AG and non-qualifying (losses less than €200 million). * Pentti (FMI) Hannelore III (FUB) – On 21–22 March, an area of low pressure drew across western Norway. In Hordaland and Sogn og Fjordane many places saw more than 100&nbsp;mm of precipitation in 24 hours, resulting in several landslides, which among other things led to five homes being evacuated in Nordheimsund. From 24 March an area of high pressure began to build across southern and mid Norway.<ref name="Toppe" /> The low passed over Finland leaving 20,000 without power.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sähkökatkot Pentti-myrskyn jäljiltä pääosin korjattu|url=http://yle.fi/uutiset/sahkokatkot_pentti-myrskyn_jaljilta_paaosin_korjattu/7150597|accessdate=13 August 2014|publisher=YLE|date=22 March 2014|language=Finnish}}</ref> |- | Lena (Ursula)|| {{Sort|201403008|7–11 August 2014}} || {{Sort|985|985 hPa}} || An unusually powerful area of low pressure for the time of year brought record winds to the west of Norway ahead of Ex-hurricane Bertha, the highest gust of {{convert|42.0|m/s|km/h}} was recorded at [[Kråkenes Lighthouse]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Ekstremværet Lena har blåst fra seg|url=http://met.no/Ekstremv%C3%A6ret+Lena+har+bl%C3%A5st+fra+seg.b7C_xdnIYb.ips|accessdate=10 August 2014|publisher=Norwegian Meteorological Institute|date=10 August 2014|language=Norwegian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812211656/http://met.no/Ekstremv%C3%A6ret+Lena+har+bl%C3%A5st+fra+seg.b7C_xdnIYb.ips#|archive-date=12 August 2014|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Sundfjord Otterlei|first1=Simen|last2=Hjetland|first2=Geir Bjarte|title="Lena" satte over 40 vindrekorder|url=http://www.nrk.no/hordaland/_lena_-satte-over-40-vindrekorder-1.11872095|accessdate=10 August 2014|publisher=NRK|date=10 August 2014|language=Norwegian}}</ref> |- | Alexandra & Billie || {{Sort|20141207|7–15 December 2014}} || {{Sort|950|950 hPa}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.met.fu-berlin.de/de/wetter/maps/Analyse_20141209.gif|title=December 9, 2014 surface analysis|date=9 December 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref><br />{{Sort|975|975 hPa}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.met.fu-berlin.de/de/wetter/maps/Analyse_20141213.gif|title=December 13, 2014 surface analysis|date=13 December 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref> || * Explosive cyclogenesis over North Atlantic brought severe winds, flooding and thunderstorms to the northwestern parts of the UK. More than 30 000 households were left without power.<ref>{{cite news|title=Power restored as 'weather bomb' storm subsides|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-30402293|accessdate=10 December 2014|newspaper=BBC|date=10 December 2014}}</ref> * A secondary low to Alexandra named Billie by FUB was named by SMHI as Alexander formed over southern England and developed en route to the Baltic region.<ref>{{cite news|title=Stormen Alexander har dragit förbi|url=http://www.smhi.se/nyhetsarkiv/stormen-alexander-har-dragit-forbi-1.82363|accessdate=14 December 2014|publisher=SMHI|date=13 December 2014|language=Swedish}}</ref> Two people were killed in Germany.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.haz.de/Nachrichten/Panorama/Uebersicht/Zwei-Tote-nach-Sturm-Billie-in-Deutschland|title=Zwei Tote nach Sturm "Billie" in Deutschland|date=14 December 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref> |- |}
=== Severe European windstorms since 2015 === {| class="wikitable sortable" |- ! Name (other name) !! Dates !! Minimum pressure !! Meteorological history |- | Elon, Felix & Hermann || {{Sort|10150107|7–19 January 2015}} || {{Sort|970|970 hPa}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.met.fu-berlin.de/de/wetter/maps/Analyse_20150109.gif|title=January 9, 2015 surface analysis|date=9 January 2015|accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref><br />{{Sort|955|955 hPa}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.met.fu-berlin.de/de/wetter/maps/Prognose_20150109.gif|title=January 10, 2015 surface analysis|date=9 January 2015|accessdate=11 January 2015}}</ref><br />{{Sort|950|950 hPa}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.met.fu-berlin.de/de/wetter/maps/Analyse_20150115.gif|title=January 15, 2015 surface analysis|date=15 January 2015|accessdate=23 January 2015}}</ref> || * Elon (Dagmar)<ref>{{cite news|last1=Siewertsen|first1=Bjarne|title=Stormen hedder Dagmar|url=http://www.dmi.dk/nyheder/arkiv/nyheder-2015/01/stormen-hedder-dagmar/|accessdate=9 January 2015|publisher=DMI|date=8 January 2015|language=Danish}}</ref> A gust of {{convert|113|mph|km/h}} was recorded in [[Stornoway]], [[Isle of Lewis]] – the strongest gust since the station first began recording in 1970.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Duffy|first1=Owen|title=Engineers battle to reopen Scotland's railways after 110mph winds|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2015/jan/09/scotland-railways-reopen-after-110mph-winds|accessdate=9 January 2015|publisher=Guardian|date=9 January 2015}}</ref> * Felix (Egon)<ref>{{cite news|title=Weekendens anden storm hedder Egon|url=http://www.dmi.dk/nyheder/arkiv/nyheder-2015/01/weekendens-anden-storm-hedder-egon/|accessdate=9 January 2015|publisher=DMI|date=9 January 2015|language=Danish}}</ref> Also named as extreme weather Nina in Norway.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bækken|first1=Trond Ivar|title=Lørdag kommer "Nina"|url=http://artikkel.yr.no/lordag-kommer-_nina_-1.12141167|accessdate=9 January 2015|publisher=yr.no|date=9 January 2015|language=Norwegian}}</ref> * Hermann, named Rachel by a private UK forecaster, which was used in some news media.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ahlstrom|first1=Dick|title=Storm-naming system yet to be put in place as Rachel peters out|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/science/storm-naming-system-yet-to-be-put-in-place-as-rachel-peters-out-1.2067463|accessdate=17 January 2015|publisher=Irish Times|date=15 January 2015}}</ref> |- | Ole || {{Sort|20150206|6–9 February 2015}} || 965 hPa || Ole named by the Norwegian Meteorological Institute (Othmar FUB, Laina Finland) brought record breaking winds to some locations in Northern Norway and Swedish Lapland.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ole gav några nya vindrekord i norr|url=http://www.smhi.se/nyhetsarkiv/ole-gav-nagra-nya-vindrekord-i-norr-1.84643|accessdate=9 February 2015|publisher=SMHI|date=9 February 2015|language=Swedish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Her blåste det mest under ekstremværet Ole|url=http://met.no/Ekstremv%C3%A6ret+Ole+satte+nye+rekorder.b7C_xdrKYd.ips|accessdate=9 February 2015|publisher=Norwegian Meteorological Institute|date=9 February 2015|language=Norwegian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209202612/http://met.no/Ekstremv%C3%A6ret+Ole+satte+nye+rekorder.b7C_xdrKYd.ips#|archive-date=9 February 2015|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref> |- | [[Cyclone Niklas|Niklas]] || {{Sort|20150329|29 March–3 April 2015}} || 971.4 hPa<ref name="Wetterdienst">{{cite news|last1=Haeseler |first1=Susanne |last2=Lefebvre |first2=Christiana |title=Orkantief NIKLAS wütet am 31.März 2015 über Deutschland |url=http://www.dwd.de/bvbw/generator/DWDWWW/Content/Oeffentlichkeit/KU/KU2/KU24/besondere__ereignisse__global/stuerme/20150331__NIKLAS__deutschland,templateId=raw,property=publicationFile.pdf/20150331_NIKLAS_deutschland.pdf |accessdate=1 April 2015 |publisher=Deutscher Wetterdienst |date=1 April 2015 |language=German }}{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> ||Niklas is believed to be one of the strongest storms in Germany in recent years,<ref>{{cite news|title=Storm Niklas kills at least three, stops trains|url=http://www.thelocal.de/20150331/storm-shuts-down-nrw-train-lines|accessdate=31 March 2015|publisher=The Local (de)|date=31 March 2015}}</ref> preceded by the low Mike which also brought hurricane strength winds to Europe. also named Lentestorm (spring storm) by KNMI, affected areas of western and central Europe with widespread disruption to air, shipping and road transport at the end of March 2015. The storm also caused forestry and property damage, power outages, and led to the loss of several lives. |- | Zeljko || {{sort|20150722|22–30 July 2015}} || 995 hPa || An unusually strong storm developed over the North Sea for the time of year, which according to KNMI is the strongest storm of its type witnessed in the Netherlands during summer.<ref>{{cite news|title=Weeralarm voor zware zomerstorm |url=http://www.knmi.nl/cms/content/123603/weeralarm_voor_zware_zomerstorm |accessdate=26 July 2015 |publisher=KMNI |date=26 July 2015 |language=Dutch |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150728193909/http://www.knmi.nl/cms/content/123603/weeralarm_voor_zware_zomerstorm |archivedate=28 July 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Bachmeier |first1=Scott |title=Strong July storm “Zeljko” affects parts of central Europe « CIMSS Satellite Blog |url=http://cimss.ssec.wisc.edu/goes/blog/archives/19018 |accessdate=14 June 2018 |work=cimss.ssec.wisc.edu |date=25 July 2015}}</ref><sup>([[:nl:Storm van 25 juli 2015|NL]])</sup> |- | Uwe || {{sort|20151206|6–11 December 2015}}|| 944 hPa || <ref>{{cite news|last1=Finsson|first1=Luna|title=Extreme Storm to Hit Iceland: Stay Inside!|url=http://www.icenews.is/2015/12/07/extreme-storm-to-hit-iceland-stay-inside/|accessdate=7 December 2015|publisher=Icenews|date=7 December 2015}}</ref> A severe storm affected Iceland, and was given the local name Diddú on Twitter.<ref name="Sigurjonsdottir">{{cite news|last1=Sigurjonsdottir|first1=Sol|title=Voldsomt uvær herjer på Island – myndighetene har erklært unntakstilstand|url=http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/uriks/Voldsomt-uvar-herjer-pa-Island---myndighetene-har-erklart-unntakstilstand-8274872.html|accessdate=8 December 2015|publisher=Aftenposten|date=7 December 2015|language=Norwegian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Storm Diddú has passed – but who is Diddú?|url=http://icelandmonitor.mbl.is/news/culture_and_living/2015/12/09/storm_diddu_has_passed_but_who_is_diddu/|accessdate=12 December 2015|publisher=Iceland Monitor|date=9 December 2015}}</ref> The storm brought maximum wind gusts of 72.6&nbsp;m/s (over 160&nbsp;mph) to the East Iceland weather station at Hallormsstaðaháls, with hurricane-force winds reported from 33 weather stations in the country, and was the worst storm to affect Iceland since 1991.<ref name="Sigurjonsdottir"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Iceland sees double hurricane force winds|url=http://icelandmonitor.mbl.is/news/nature_and_travel/2015/12/08/iceland_sees_double_hurricane_force_winds/|accessdate=8 December 2015|publisher=Iceland Monitor|date=8 December 2015}}</ref> |- | [[Cyclone Egon|Egon]] || {{sort|20170112|12–13 January 2017}}|| 981 hPa || Egon was the first storm to surpass the Perils.org reporting threshold of €200 million since storm Niklas in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=Europe's Windstorm Egon to Cost Insurers an Estimated US$223.3M: PERILS|url=http://www.insurancejournal.com/news/international/2017/02/23/442629.htm|accessdate=21 March 2017|publisher=Insurance Journal|date=23 February 2017}}</ref> |- | Thomas (Doris) || {{sort|20170223|23–28 February 2017}} || 974 hPa ||<ref>{{cite news|title=European windstorm Thomas/Doris could be costliest of season|url=http://www.artemis.bm/blog/2017/02/24/european-windstorm-thomasdoris-could-be-costliest-of-season/|accessdate=23 August 2017|publisher=Artemis.bm - The Catastrophe Bond, Insurance Linked Securities & Investment, Reinsurance Capital, Alternative Risk Transfer and Weather Risk Management Blog|date=24 February 2017}}</ref> |- | [[Cyclone Zeus|Zeus]] || {{sort|20170106|5–8 March 2017}}|| 996 hPa ||Zeus affected France on a trajectory stretching from Brittany to the Italian border. ''Zeus'' was not named by a national meteorological agency but was widely used in French media, believed to be a misappellation of another low named by the Free University of Berlin charts |- | [[Cyclone Xavier (2017)|Xavier]] || {{sort|20171004|4–6 October 2017}} || 985 hPa || |- | [[Hurricane Ophelia (2017)|Ex&#8209;Ophelia]] || {{sort|20171016|16–17 October 2017}}|| 959 hPa || |- | [[Cyclone Herwart|Herwart]] || {{sort|20171028|28–29 October 2017}} || 970 hPa || |- | [[Cyclone Eleanor/Burglind|Eleanor (Burglind)]] || {{sort|20180102|2–3 January 2018}} || 966 hPa || |- | [[Cyclone David/Friederike|Friederike (David)]] || {{sort|20180118|18 January 2018}} || 974 hPa || Schiphol closed. Record winds recorded in Rotterdam. Deutsche Bahn cancelled all long distance services. At least 10 dead in Germany.<ref name=friederikesd>http://www.sueddeutsche.de/panorama/fernverkehr-friederike-deutsche-bahn-nimmt-betrieb-wieder-auf-1.3832103</ref> Record winds recorded at [[Brocken]]: 203 km/h. Damage estimated at 1 billion EUR<ref>{{cite news|title="Friederike" kostet rund eine Milliarde Euro|url=https://www.tagesschau.de/inland/sturmschaeden-friederike-101.html|accessdate=25 January 2018|work=Tagesschau (ARD)|date=25 January 2018}}</ref> to 2.6 billion EUR<ref>http://www.businessinsurance.com/article/20180126/NEWS06/912318787/Storm-Friederike-insured-losses-as-high-as-$322B-AIR-Worldwide</ref>. Deutsche Bahn has decided to hire an additional 150 foresters because of damaged incurred by the storm.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.faz.net/aktuell/gesellschaft/ungluecke/friederike-bahn-will-mehr-in-sturmsicherheit-investieren-15409661.html | title=Bahn will mehr Geld in Sturmsicherheit investieren | work=Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung | date=21 January 2018 | accessdate=28 August 2018 }}</ref> |- | [[2018–19 European windstorm season]] | | | |- |}
